 =20
   =20
      Venture Global
   =20
 =20

Love these guys:

Michael Sabel=C2=A0and his partner, both industry novices, have made a fort=
une virtually overnight by building from scratch one of the world=E2=80=99s=
 largest gas exporters. They have also made some powerful enemies.
Here at this sprawling facility spanning about 630 acres in the wetlands ou=
tside New Orleans, Sabel said his company,=C2=A0Venture Global LNG, is on p=
ace to leapfrog competitors and to rival Qatar as one of the world=E2=80=99=
s top exporters of liquefied natural gas by 2030.
But he must navigate a nasty feud with some of the industry=E2=80=99s bigge=
st names.=C2=A0
Venture Global=E2=80=99s earliest customers, including the oil giants BP an=
d Shell, say the upstart company is ripping them off. =E2=80=A6
BP and Shell argue that under the long-term contracts they signed over the =
past decade with Venture Global, they should have begun receiving LNG cargo=
es months ago, which they could sell through their vast trading arms. Inste=
ad, when the Ukraine war broke out, and LNG prices soared, Venture Global s=
old its gas at higher prices on the spot market=E2=80=94raking in more than=
 $14 billion in sales.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s very unusual, and it=E2=80=99s very disappointing,=E2=
=80=9D Shell CEO=C2=A0Wael Sawan=C2=A0said in a November interview. =E2=80=
=9CThis is, of course, a project that was underpinned by the offtake agreem=
ents that companies like ours provided.=E2=80=9DVenture Global counters tha=
t the contracts require it to deliver LNG to those early customers only whe=
n its first plant in Louisiana, called Calcasieu Pass, is finished. And it =
says even though the plant has shipped more than 200 cargoes, it isn=E2=80=
=99t technically complete. Twenty-one months after Venture Global=E2=80=99s=
 first overseas shipment, BP, Shell and other early buyers are still waitin=
g, and seething.=C2=A0

We  talked about this in August, but now there is a Wall Street Journal pro=
file of Venture Global and the dispute, and it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is really not=
 more complicated than I thought it was? Venture Global has long-term suppl=
y contracts with customers like BP and Shell, requiring it to sell them LNG=
 cargoes at fixed prices. It signed these contracts well before it built it=
s facility, =E2=80=9Cputting the project on the map and giving big banks co=
nfidence to provide financing=E2=80=9D to build it, as the Journal reports.=
 The customers got discounted prices in exchange for taking a risk on an un=
proven new venture; Venture Global got commitments that allowed it to build=
 its facility. The way those contracts work is that Venture Global has to s=
tart delivering gas to the buyers when work on its plant is done and it ent=
ers commercial operation. I wrote in August:
It has a plant in Louisiana that =E2=80=9Chas yet to enter commercial opera=
tions,=E2=80=9D but that nevertheless produces and sells LNG. There is some=
 philosophical distinction there that eludes me: Intuitively, if you have a=
 factory that is producing and selling LNG, that would seem to be a commerc=
ial operation, but apparently if there=E2=80=99s something wrong with your =
steam generators then, no, not commercial yet, fine.
And then the spot price of natural gas shot up and Venture Global started p=
roducing LNG and selling it in the spot market, arguing that, while the pla=
nt is complete enough to export LNG, it is not complete complete, and so Ve=
nture Global doesn=E2=80=99t have to fulfill the contracts yet. =E2=80=9CDo=
 not flip the metaphysical switch that turns your not-in-commercial-operati=
on plant into an in-commercial-operation plant,=E2=80=9D I said. =E2=80=9CI=
n March, it told its long-term buyers that serious malfunctions in the Calc=
asieu Pass power system would delay their contracted cargoes,=E2=80=9D says=
 the Journal, though those malfunctions were not serious enough to delay th=
e=C2=A0other=C2=A0cargoes, the ones it is selling at much higher prices in =
the spot market. The long-term buyers do not like it. =E2=80=9CWhen the vas=
t majority of your customers are pursuing some form of litigation against y=
ou, it=E2=80=99s time to look in the mirror,=E2=80=9D the Shell spokesman s=
aid. Venture Global disagrees:

Sabel said customers knew from the beginning there would be an extended per=
iod to get the plant fully operational and the company would sell cargoes t=
o others during that period before fulfilling long-term contracts.
=E2=80=9CYou get all-time low prices, we get to finish the facility,=E2=80=
=9D he said.

I hope that eventually they get the facility just about finished, but they =
don=E2=80=99t, like, paint one last rivet. And then they say =E2=80=9Coops,=
 still not finished, see, unpainted rivet,=E2=80=9D and keep selling LNG at=
 high prices to spot buyers. (I hope Shell and BP grumble and buy at spot p=
rices too!) And then eventually when gas prices drop and it=E2=80=99s less =
uneconomical for Venture Global to sell at the contract prices, they say =
=E2=80=9Cokay fine fine=E2=80=9D and paint the rivet. What a great trade.=
=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      AI signals
   =20
 =20

Two ways to use a computer to generate trading signals would be:
=09Think about subtle characteristics of a company that might be good or ba=
d for that company. Develop a hypothesis =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cexecutives=
 who say =E2=80=98I=E2=80=99 on earnings calls are bad narcissists, but exe=
cutives who say =E2=80=98we=E2=80=99 on earnings calls are good inclusive l=
eaders=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then use a computer to crunch the data a=
nd evaluate the hypothesis. Take the hypotheses that are good =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the signals that turn out to work =E2=80=94=C2=A0and program them into a=
 trading model, which uses the signals to buy and sell stocks.=09Just ask a=
 computer =E2=80=9Cis this company good or what,=E2=80=9D and if the comput=
er says =E2=80=9Cyeah it=E2=80=99s good=E2=80=9D you buy the stock.

The advantage of the first method is that it is comprehensible; you can, at=
 some level, explain your strategy, because you have reasons for every sign=
al. Also those signals are more likely to be robust, less likely to be just=
 statistical artifacts, if there is some explicable reasoning behind them.
The advantage of the second method is, what if the computer is smarter than=
 you? What if it sees subtle patterns that you miss?
Anyway here=E2=80=99s   Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Justina Lee on =E2=80=9Cwhat ar=
tificial-intelligence proponents are dreaming up these days, thanks to the =
computational firepower of language models like ChatGPT=E2=80=9D:

At its core, linguistic data-crunching seeks to help quants get better at p=
redicting the future by analyzing the meaning of the text behind the number=
s.=C2=A0
Over at AllianceBernstein, data scientists Andrew Chin and Yuyu Fan are goi=
ng all-in on AI tools to find hidden meanings in corporate spiel. Not every=
 attempt has worked. For instance, when they dug into how Chinese companies=
 summarize on-site visits from brokers, they found that the more complex th=
e text =E2=80=94 like the length of sentences and unnecessary words =E2=80=
=94 the more evidence that the firm in question is struggling.
On the other hand, the number of words divided by the length of the broker =
event, a proxy for speaking speed, didn=E2=80=99t mean much. In US earnings=
 calls, they studied the use of the =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=9D pronoun as a sign =
of collaboration and unity. That also proved meaningless.
=E2=80=9CWe really try to generate a broad set of signals =E2=80=94 sometim=
es hundreds =E2=80=94 but it doesn=E2=80=99t mean all of them will work,=E2=
=80=9D said Fan, a senior data scientist at the $669 billion manager.
Whereas machine reading used to rely on counting positive and negative word=
s, the large language models behind chatbots are far better at parsing cont=
ext even across meandering paragraphs. These robots not only purport to str=
ucture the unstructured, they also promise to automate research tasks and g=
enerate fresh trading ideas at breakneck speed. And the introduction of Cha=
tGPT alone =E2=80=94 which has ingested enough text that it has a good gras=
p of all subjects =E2=80=94 is a regime shift. Academic researchers have fo=
und that simply telling the chatbot to rate if a news headline is good or b=
ad for a stock has produced better results than prior methods.

You can construct a query like =E2=80=9Cdoes this news story indicate that =
the company=E2=80=99s leadership team is collaborative and not using comple=
x answers to hide the truth,=E2=80=9D or you can construct a query like =E2=
=80=9Ccomputer, would you buy this stock?=E2=80=9D I guess you=E2=80=99d fe=
el better about your own contributions if you asked the more complicated qu=
estions. Like, you are in charge here and the computer is just helping with=
 the analysis. But =E2=80=9Csimply telling the chatbot to rate if a news he=
adline is good or bad for a stock has produced better results than prior me=
thods.=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      Celebrity SPACs
   =20
 =20

For a while, not that long ago, there was a huge boom in special purpose ac=
quisition companies. A SPAC is basically some financial quasi-celebrity rai=
sing a bunch of money to go out and take a company public, and bigger finan=
cial celebrities tended to get better results. If you were, for instance, C=
hamath Palihapitiya, who became famous as the  SPAC King, you could raise a=
 lot of money for a lot of SPACs, get meetings with a lot of high-profile p=
rivate companies, close attractive deals with them and make a lot of money.=
 (For yourself, anyway. Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s SPACs  did not perform parti=
cularly well for his investors, but nobody=E2=80=99s perfect.)
Palihapitiya is a somewhat arbitrary celebrity, though, and pretty quickly =
the promotors of the SPAC boom realized that you could just get=C2=A0real=
=C2=A0celebrities to do SPACs. In 2021,  the New York Times reported on SPA=
Cs promoted by, among other people, Jay-Z, Shaquille O=E2=80=99Neal,=C2=A0S=
erena Williams and=C2=A0Alex Rodriguez. (Also in 2021, the US Securities an=
d Exchange Commission  put out an investor alert warning: =E2=80=9CNever in=
vest in a SPAC based solely on a celebrity=E2=80=99s involvement.=E2=80=9D)=
 I  wrote at the time that =E2=80=9Cone possibility is that this is ineffic=
ient, and every celebrity has a SPAC because the SPAC market is unbelievabl=
y frothy right now,=E2=80=9D so there was plenty of money to spend on celeb=
rity marketing. But, I went on:
Another possibility is that this is efficient, in a goofy way. It is probab=
ly true that, in the business of sourcing and negotiating deals with privat=
e companies, random celebrities do have certain advantages over experienced=
 mergers-and-acquisitions bankers and semi-retired corporate operators.=C2=
=A0There is undoubtedly a set of company founders who would be really excit=
ed to take a meeting with noted former Citigroup banker Michael Klein, but =
there is another set of founders who would be much more excited to take a m=
eeting with noted current Warriors guard Steph Curry. The latter group is p=
robably larger, and it is not obvious that it would be worse for investors.
Obviously this is an empirical question: Either celebrity-led SPACs did=C2=
=A0worse=C2=A0than banker-led SPACs, or they did=C2=A0better.=C2=A0(And the=
 data is basically in, since the SPAC boom has emphatically ended.) And her=
e is =E2=80=9CCelebrity SPACs: Advantageous or Gimmicky?=E2=80=9D by Emre K=
uvvet in the Journal of Investing:
Celebrity involvement with special purpose acquisition companies (SPACs) ha=
s received intense criticism by the media and the SEC. Should investment ma=
nagers be wary of celebrity SPACs? We examine the role of celebrities in th=
e SPAC process and find that celebrity SPACs have more fundings, higher-qua=
lity SPAC intermediaries, higher-quality target firms, higher returns, and =
shorter duration of target acquisitions. Sponsors of celebrity SPACs also h=
ave more =E2=80=9Cskin in the game.=E2=80=9D We show that while celebrity c=
hairpeople, CEOs, and board members have positive impacts on the SPAC proce=
ss, celebrity advisors do not have such positive effects.
=E2=80=9CCelebrity advisor=E2=80=9D is just, like, throw some marketing mon=
ey at a celebrity; =E2=80=9Ccelebrity board member=E2=80=9D is, Shaq might =
show up at the meeting with the target to close the deal. That turns out to=
 actually be worth something.

 =20
   =20
      Binance is law-abiding now
   =20
 =20

Crypto is mature enough by now that there are some good running bits, some =
callbacks to old jokes. Tether has spent years telling anyone who will list=
en that it is just months away from releasing an audit, and everyone has a =
good laugh each time.=C2=A0And Binance has spent years  claiming that it wa=
s located nowhere, to the point that when  Chinese police reportedly raided=
 its Shanghai office, Binance  replied that=C2=A0it =E2=80=9Chas no fixed o=
ffices in Shanghai or China, so it makes no sense that police raided on any=
 offices and shut them down.=E2=80=9D Classic.
But then Binance  pleaded guilty to a bunch of money laundering charges in =
US federal court, agreeing to pay $4.3 billion in penalties and install a c=
ompliance monitor to be generally more law-abiding. Its founder and chief e=
xecutive officer, Changpeng =E2=80=9CCZ=E2=80=9D Zhao, also pleaded guilty =
and stepped down as CEO. You might think this would put an end to the =E2=
=80=9Cno location=E2=80=9D bit but, no, it=E2=80=99s too good. The  Financi=
al Times reports on the new CEO, Richard Teng:

Teng on Tuesday declined to reveal where the exchange was based. He also sa=
id Binance has undergone audits in jurisdictions where it is regulated, but=
 declined to name the audit firms involved.
=E2=80=9CWhy do you feel so entitled to those answers?=E2=80=9D Teng asked =
at the FT Crypto and Digital Assets Summit in London, adding that the compa=
ny provides the necessary information to regulators. =E2=80=9CIs there a ne=
ed for us to share all of this information publicly? No.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

I guess not, no, I guess it=E2=80=99s fine for a financial institution trus=
ted with billions of dollars of customer money not to be located in any par=
ticular jurisdiction? Binance=E2=80=99s  plea agreement requires it to hire=
 a monitor to write reports on its anti-money-laundering compliance and sha=
re them with the US Department of Justice, and requires Binance to =E2=80=
=9Cprovide the Monitor with access to all =E2=80=A6=C2=A0facilities, and em=
ployees, as reasonably requested by the Monitor, that fall within the scope=
 of the Mandate of the Monitor,=E2=80=9D so I suppose the Justice Departmen=
t can find out where Binance is located, but maybe not? Maybe the monitor w=
ill be like =E2=80=9Chey can I visit headquarters=E2=80=9D and Binance will=
 say =E2=80=9Cwhy do you feel entitled to that=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0

